{{Galaxy cluster | name = [[Abell catalogue|Abell]] 2744 | image = Pandora's Cluster – Abell 2744.jpg | caption = Abell 2744, nicknamed Pandora's Cluster. The [[Galaxy|galaxies]] in the [[Galaxy cluster|cluster]] make up less than five percent of its mass. The gas (around 20 percent) is so hot that it shines only in [[X-rays]] (coloured red in this image). The distribution of invisible [[dark matter]] (making up around 75 percent of the cluster's mass) is coloured here in blue. | credit = | epoch = [[Epoch (astronomy)#Julian years and J2000|J2000]] | ra = {{RA|00|14|19.51}} <ref name="HubbleSite">{{cite web |title=Pandora's Cluster – Clash of the Titans |publisher=[[NASA]] |url=http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2011/17/ }}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-30|23|19.18}} <ref name="HubbleSite" /> | constellation = [[Sculptor (constellation)|Sculptor]] | member_no = | richness = 3<ref name="ACO">{{cite journal | last1 = Abell | first1 = George O. | authorlink1 = George O. Abell | last2 = Corwin | first2 = Harold G., Jr. | last3 = Olowin | first3 = Ronald P. |date=May 1989 | title = A catalog of rich clusters of galaxies | journal = Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series | volume = 70 | issue = May 1989 | pages = 1–138 | format = PDF | issn = 0067-0049 | bibcode = 1989ApJS...70....1A | doi = 10.1086/191333 | accessdate = 13 March 2012 | url = http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?bibcode=1989ApJS...70....1A&page_ind=0&epage_ind=137&type=PRINTER&data_type=PDF_HIGH&email=&emailsize=500&emailsplit=YES&send=GET&verified=YES }}</ref> | bmtype = III<ref name="ACO" /> | velocity_dispersion = | redshift = 0.30800<ref name="NED">{{cite web | url = http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?objname=Abell+2744&extend=no | title = NED results for object ABELL 2744 | publisher = NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database (NED) | accessdate = 17 March 2012 | postscript = . }}</ref> | distance = {{convert|1221|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} {{hub|0.705}} <ref name="NED" /> | temperature = | mass = | luminosity = | flux = (5.805 ± 4.7%){{e|-13}} [[erg]] s<sup>−1</sup> cm<sup>−2</sup> (0.1—2.4 [[electron volt|keV]]) <ref name="NED" /> | other_names = Pandora's Cluster }}
'''Abell 2744''', nicknamed '''Pandora's Cluster''', is a giant [[galaxy cluster]] resulting from the simultaneous pile-up of at least four separate, smaller galaxy clusters that took place over a span of 350 million years.<ref name="HubbleSite" /> The [[Galaxy|galaxies]] in the cluster make up less than five percent of its mass.<ref name="HubbleSite" /> The gas (around 20&nbsp;percent) is so hot that it shines only in [[X-rays]].<ref name="HubbleSite" /> [[Dark matter]] makes up around 75&nbsp;percent of the cluster's mass.<ref name="HubbleSite" />
This cluster also shows a [[radio halo]] along with several other [[List of Abell clusters|Abell clusters]]. It has a strong central halo, along with an extended tail, which could either be relic radiation, or an extension of the central halo.<ref>{{cite journal |arxiv=astro-ph/0101418 |title=A Comparison of Radio and X-Ray Morphologies of Four Clusters of Galaxies Containing Radio Halos |first1=F. |last1=Govoni |first2=T. A. |last2=Ensslin |first3=L. |last3=Feretti |first4=G. |last4=Giovannini |date=23 January 2001 |doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20010115 |volume=369 |journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics |pages=441–449 |bibcode=2001A&A...369..441G}}</ref>
Renato Dupke, a member of the team that discovered the Cluster, explained the origin of the name in an interview: "We nicknamed it ‘''Pandora's Cluster''’ because so many different and strange phenomena were unleashed by the collision."<ref>Renato Dupke quoted at [http://www.spacetelescope.org/news/heic1111/ Pandora's Cluster - a galactic crash investigation] Press release of 22 June 2011</ref>
==Gallery== <gallery> File:Swimming in Sculptor.jpg|Giant galaxy cluster Abell 2744 observed as part of the Frontier Fields programme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming in Sculptor|url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/images/potw1610a/|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> File:Hubble sees ghost light from dead galaxies in galaxy cluster Abell 2744.jpg|The galaxies that are not coloured blue are either in the foreground or background and are not part of the cluster.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hubble sees ghost light from dead galaxies in galaxy cluster Abell 2744|url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/images/opo1443a/|website=www.spacetelescope.org|publisher=ESA/Hubble|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref> File:Heic1401a-Abell2744-20140107.jpg|Abell 2744 [[galaxy cluster]] - [[Hubble Space Telescope#Frontier Fields program|Hubble Frontier Fields view]] (7 January 2014).<ref name="NASA-20140107">{{cite news |last1=Clavin |first1=Whitney |last2=Jenkins |first2=Ann |last3=Villard |first3=Ray |title=NASA's Hubble and Spitzer Team up to Probe Faraway Galaxies |url=http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?release=2014-007 |date=7 January 2014 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=8 January 2014 }}</ref> File:14-283-Abell2744-DistantGalaxies-20141016.jpg|Abell 2744 [[galaxy cluster]] - extremely distant [[galaxies]] revealed by [[gravitational lensing]] (16 October 2014).<ref name="NASA-20141016">{{cite web |last=Chou |first=Felecia |last2=Weaver |first2=Donna |title=RELEASE 14-283 - NASA’s Hubble Finds Extremely Distant Galaxy through Cosmic Magnifying Glass |url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2014/october/nasa-s-hubble-finds-extremely-distant-galaxy-through-cosmic-magnifying-glass/ |date=16 October 2014 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=17 October 2014 }}</ref> </gallery>
