[[File:Cardinal gems.png|right|thumb|The five '''cardinal gems'''. Clockwise from top: [[sapphire]], [[ruby]], [[emerald]], [[amethyst]], [[diamond]].]] '''Cardinal gems''' are [[gemstones]] which have traditionally been considered precious above all others. The classification of the cardinal gems dates back to antiquity, and was largely determined by ceremonial or religious use and rarity.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=The Illustrated Bead Bible: Terms, Tips & Techniques|author1=Geary, T.F.|author2=Whalen, D.|date=2008|publisher=Sterling Pub.|isbn=9781402723537|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5abGjJ54mSoC&pg=PA69|page=69|accessdate=2015-07-19}}</ref> The term has largely fallen out of use.
The five traditional cardinal gems are: *[[amethyst]] (purple) – Considered rare and precious in the Old World, until large deposits were found in Brazil. *[[diamond]] (white) *[[emerald]] (green) *[[ruby]] (red) *[[sapphire]] (blue)
