{{neuroscientist-stub}}

'''Jean François Aimé Théophile Philippe Gaudin''' or '''Jean François Aimée Gottlieb Philippe Gaudin''' (1766 in [[Longirod]], canton de Vaud &ndash; 1833) was a Swiss [[pastor]], professor and botanist. He was the author of the monumental "Flora Helvetica" in 7 volumes.

== Tributes ==
He gave his name to the annual grass genus ''[[Gaudinia]]'' belonging to the Poeae.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

== See also ==
* [[Jaques Étienne Gay]] (1786-1864), a Swiss-French botanist and one of the most famous  students of botanist Jean François Aimée Gaudin

{{botanist|Gaudin}}

